5. Compare and contrast Hierarchical (Tree) structure and Linear (Sequential) structure
Hierarchical (Tree) Structure
The hierarchical structure organizes a website in a top-down manner, where the home page
is the root and other pages are arranged as main categories and sub-categories. Users can
move freely between sections using menus and links. This structure is ideal for large 
and complex websites.
Characteristics:
Clear parent–child relationship
Easy to expand (scalable)
Supports multiple navigation paths
Good for information-heavy websites
Example:
A University website where the Home page leads to Admissions, Departments, Library, 
Alumni, etc., and each department has its own sub-pages.

Linear (Sequential) Structure
The linear structure presents content in a fixed order, where users must follow one step
after another. Navigation is controlled, and skipping steps is usually not allowed. This 
structure is best for task-based or instructional websites.
Characteristics:
Step-by-step navigation
Simple and guided flow
Less user control
Not suitable for large websites
Example:
An online examination system or checkout process where users must complete one step before
moving to the next.

Comparison Table:
Basis	          Hierarchical Structure	      Linear Structure
Navigation	         Multiple paths              	Single path
User freedom	     High	                        Low
Website size	     Large websites	                Small / task-based
Flexibility	         High	                        Limited   

6. Explain the “Three-Click Rule” and its significance in UX design

The Three-Click Rule states that a user should be able to find any information on a website 
within three clicks. If users take more than three clicks, they may feel confused, frustrated, 
or lose interest.

Importance in UX Design:
Reduces cognitive friction
Improves ease of use
Saves user time
Increases user satisfaction
Decreases bounce rate

Example:
If a student wants to find admission requirements, it should be reachable within three 
clicks:
Home → Admissions → Requirements
This rule encourages designers to build clear menus, logical structure, and efficient 
navigation.

7. “Plan before you do.” How Card Sorting and Flowcharts help in planning a website’s structure
Card Sorting
Card sorting is a technique where content items are written on cards, and users are asked 
to group them in a way that makes sense to them.

How it helps:
Reveals how users think
Helps create logical categories
Improves menu labeling
Reduces user confusion
Example:
Users may group “Courses”, “Departments”, and “Faculty” under “Academics”.

Flowcharts
Flowcharts are visual diagrams that show how users move from one page to another on a 
website.

How it helps:
Shows navigation paths clearly
Identifies unnecessary steps
Improves user journey
Helps developers and designers understand structure

Conclusion:
By using card sorting and flowcharts, designers can plan the website structure properly 
before development, resulting in a simple, organized, and user-friendly website.

