9. A user visits a website but leaves within 10 seconds because they cannot find the navigation menu, 
which is hidden behind a small icon on a desktop screen. Analyze this design failure using the ”KISS” 
(Keep It Simple) principle.
Scenario Recap

User visits a website.
Navigation menu is hidden behind a small icon (like a hamburger menu).
On a desktop screen, this is unexpected.
User leaves within 10 seconds.
KISS Principle
KISS = Keep It Simple, Stupid (or "Keep It Simple and Straightforward")
The idea: avoid unnecessary complexity in design.
Users should understand and use the interface immediately without confusion.
Analysis of Design Failure
Unnecessary Complexity
Hiding the navigation menu behind a small icon adds extra cognitive effort.
On desktop screens, users expect visible menus, not hidden ones.

Poor Usability
Users couldn’t easily find what they were looking for.
Frustration causes high bounce rate (leaving within 10 seconds).

Violation of KISS
The interface is not simple or intuitive.
Keeping the navigation visible on desktops would have kept it simple.

Impact
Website loses visitors.
User experience suffers.
Potentially reduces conversions or engagement.
How to Fix (Following KISS)
Show the full navigation menu on desktops instead of hiding it.
Only use collapsible menus on mobile screens where space is limited.
Make important elements easy to find and use.

10. An e-commerce website has a URL structure like www.shop.com/prod?id=55&cat=9. Explain 
why this is bad for both users and Search Engines (SEO), and propose a better structure using 
Page Slugs
For Users:
Unreadable & Confusing: Users cannot understand what the page is about just by looking at the URL. prod?id=55&cat=9 tells nothing about the product.
Difficult to Remember or Share: URLs with parameters like ?id=55&cat=9 are hard to memorize or share.
Poor Trust: Users may feel uncertain about clicking a link with strange codes.


For Search Engines (SEO):

Unfriendly for Crawling: Search engines prefer URLs that describe the page content. Parameter-heavy URLs are harder 
for crawlers to index properly.
No Keywords: This URL does not include any relevant keywords like product name or category, which reduces SEO effectiveness.
Duplicate Content Risk: URLs with different parameters could point to the same product, creating duplicate content issues.

Better Structure Using Page Slugs
Page slugs are the readable part of the URL, typically derived from the product name or category.
A better URL structure is:
www.shop.com/electronics/smartphone-iphone-14

Explanation:


electronics → Category of the product


smartphone-iphone-14 → Product name as a slug


Benefits:

User-Friendly: Easy to read, understand, and share.
SEO-Friendly: Includes keywords (smartphone, iPhone 14), which improves search engine ranking.
Clean & Simple: No confusing parameters, reduces cognitive friction.




